Implementing environmental policies through Java programming is a complex task that involves integrating with various systems and processes. Below is a simplified example of how you might track and enforce emissions reductions in a manufacturing process.

```java
public class EmissionsReducer {

    private double currentEmissions;
    private double targetEmissions;

    public EmissionsReducer(double currentEmissions) {
        this.currentEmissions = currentEmissions;
        this.targetEmissions = currentEmissions * 0.75; // 25% reduction
    }

    public boolean isTargetMet() {
        return currentEmissions <= targetEmissions;
    }

    public void updateEmissions(double newEmissions) {
        currentEmissions = newEmissions;
    }

    public void enforceReduction() {
        if (!isTargetMet()) {
            System.out.println("Emissions reduction target not met. Taking corrective action.");
            // Add logic to enforce reduction measures
        } else {
            System.out.println("Emissions reduction target met.");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        EmissionsReducer reducer = new EmissionsReducer(1000.0); // Initial emissions
        reducer.enforceReduction();

        // Simulate reduction over time
        reducer.updateEmissions(750.0);
        reducer.enforceReduction();
    }
}
```

